WEBVTT

00:16.050 --> 00:17.833
Jesse:
Unfortunately, the prayers

00:17.834 --> 00:19.617
of the good people of
Los Angeles have been answered

00:19.620 --> 00:21.554
and it's raining,

00:21.555 --> 00:23.489
and nothing brings people
to angels faster

00:23.491 --> 00:25.724
than the rain.

00:25.726 --> 00:27.226
Good luck.

00:27.228 --> 00:28.427
Well, you're not
coming up with us?

00:28.429 --> 00:31.230
No.
It's raining.

00:33.334 --> 00:34.500
[ Both chuckle ]

00:35.770 --> 00:38.237
[ Sighs ]

00:38.239 --> 00:40.773
What... what are you doing?

00:40.775 --> 00:42.508
Dips.
You should try it sometime.

00:42.510 --> 00:45.210
I've been texting Christa
all these panic-faced emojis,

00:45.212 --> 00:46.629
and she's not responding.

00:46.630 --> 00:48.047
Took a cab to work this morning,
and I'm on time.

00:48.049 --> 00:50.182
What happened to your car?
Oh, clutch busted.

00:50.184 --> 00:52.051
It's gonna cost me a grand
to fix it.

00:52.053 --> 00:54.253
Why didn't you tell me?
I could have just picked you up.

00:54.255 --> 00:55.654
I drive right by you
on the way to work.

00:55.656 --> 00:57.189
How do you know I slept
at my place?

00:57.191 --> 00:59.491
Okay, player.
I was just trying to help.

00:59.493 --> 01:01.460
[ Chuckling ] God!
Christa: Hey.

01:01.462 --> 01:02.795
What are you guys doing
out here?

01:02.797 --> 01:04.463
Medevac's coming in.
I've been texting you.

01:04.464 --> 01:06.130
Is everything all right?
Yeah.
Yeah, it's raining.

01:06.133 --> 01:08.133
Traffic is horrible.
Why? Did anyone say anything?

01:08.135 --> 01:10.269
[ Elevator bell dings ]
You're late, Dr. Lorenson.
Let's go.

01:10.271 --> 01:12.104
[ Sighs ]
You three with me.

01:12.106 --> 01:13.405
Damn it.

01:13.407 --> 01:14.807
Come on. Let's go!

01:14.809 --> 01:17.543
[ Button clicking ]

01:17.545 --> 01:19.611
[ Doors close ]

01:19.613 --> 01:23.148
Dr. Lorenson, over here.

01:24.552 --> 01:26.552
[ Button clicking ]
[ Sighs ]

01:26.554 --> 01:28.687
Did you get any sleep
this afternoon?

01:28.689 --> 01:31.457
No, did you?

01:31.459 --> 01:32.624
I feel responsible.

01:32.626 --> 01:34.560
For what? We had
a few drinks at breakfast.

01:34.562 --> 01:36.695
Okay, maybe more
than a few drinks.

01:36.697 --> 01:38.363
You have the code bag tonight,
Christa.

01:40.468 --> 01:41.567
Oh, wow.

01:41.569 --> 01:43.569
O-okay.

01:43.571 --> 01:44.803
You're responsible
for all the crashes

01:44.805 --> 01:46.488
that happen at the hospital
outside the E.R.

01:46.489 --> 01:48.172
Anyone loses their pulse
upstairs, they're calling you.

01:48.175 --> 01:50.175
I know what the code bag is.

01:50.177 --> 01:51.410
[ Sighs ]

01:51.412 --> 01:52.928
It's completely random
who gets it.

01:52.929 --> 01:54.445
That's the whole point...
To catch you off guard.

01:54.448 --> 01:56.181
Well, consider me caught.

01:56.183 --> 01:57.716
You'll have everything
you need in the bag...

01:57.718 --> 01:58.968
Uh, oral airways, drugs,

01:58.969 --> 02:00.219
extra syringes, filler needles,
the phone.

02:00.221 --> 02:01.420
It's connected
to the wireless network

02:01.422 --> 02:02.888
in case you lose reception.

02:02.890 --> 02:04.556
Who do I call
in the middle of a code?

02:04.558 --> 02:05.791
It's there
if you need radiology,

02:05.793 --> 02:07.626
respiratory techs, the pharmacy.

02:07.627 --> 02:09.460
You'll still be working
your shift, of course.

02:09.463 --> 02:11.497
[ Sighs ]
When it rains, it pours, huh?

02:11.499 --> 02:13.398
[ Elevator dings ]
You can handle this,
right?

02:13.400 --> 02:15.300
Yeah, doctor, I can handle it.

02:15.302 --> 02:16.502
[ Helicopter blades whirring ]

02:17.771 --> 02:19.238
- Let's go!
- Move it!

02:19.240 --> 02:20.706
Risa:
What have you got?

02:20.708 --> 02:22.207
Boating accident.
They capsized.

02:22.209 --> 02:23.675
May have been submerged
over two hours.

02:23.677 --> 02:25.644
The boy...
Pulseless on the scene.

02:25.646 --> 02:27.212
Excuse me, Dr. Pineda.

02:27.214 --> 02:29.281
How long without a pulse?
Since we got there.

02:29.283 --> 02:30.482
At least 20 minutes of cpr.

02:30.484 --> 02:32.284
All right.
What about this one?

02:32.286 --> 02:33.685
Man: Young woman,
possible leg fracture.

02:33.687 --> 02:36.321
In and out of consciousness.
Vitals are stable.

02:36.323 --> 02:37.890
Stable!
All right, I want the boy first.

02:37.892 --> 02:39.391
What's his temperature?
What?

02:39.393 --> 02:41.260
His core temp!
How cold is he?

02:41.262 --> 02:42.561
We tried.
It said "error".

02:42.563 --> 02:44.930
Error?
Yeah,
his core temperature

02:44.932 --> 02:46.899
is too cold to register
on the machine.

02:46.901 --> 02:49.601
- Too low?
- Good. Clear!

02:49.603 --> 02:50.569
[ Woman groaning ]

02:50.571 --> 02:52.221
Neal: Okay, Sophie.
All right.

02:52.222 --> 02:53.872
[ Device beeps ]
Temperature... 90.1.

02:53.874 --> 02:54.873
We have to get her warmed
immediately.

02:54.875 --> 02:56.341
Get me a bear hugger.

02:56.343 --> 02:57.392
[ Groaning continues ]

02:57.393 --> 02:58.442
All right, all right, all right.

02:58.445 --> 03:00.245
Let's get her restrained,
please!

03:00.247 --> 03:01.613
Get her restrained, please.

03:01.615 --> 03:03.282
Why is she trying
to get undressed?

03:03.284 --> 03:04.750
It's called
paradoxical undressing.

03:04.752 --> 03:06.485
It's a sign
of stage III hypothermia

03:06.487 --> 03:08.253
and evidence
of brain dysfunction.

03:08.255 --> 03:10.389
All right. Let's help her
out of her clothes, please.

03:11.358 --> 03:13.358
I think she has a broken femur.

03:13.360 --> 03:15.627
Aah.
Maybe from the boat capsizing.

03:15.629 --> 03:18.764
Let me have a temporary splint!
Can't wait for casting.

03:18.766 --> 03:20.365
This girl needs warmth
more than anything.

03:20.367 --> 03:21.533
[ Groaning continues ]

03:21.535 --> 03:23.602
Let's go, please.
Come on.

03:23.603 --> 03:25.670
Okay, 20-something male,
asystolic in the field,

03:25.673 --> 03:27.406
drowning and hypothermia.

03:27.408 --> 03:29.274
Temp feels like 80s.

03:29.276 --> 03:31.977
Mama, we're gonna need
a core temp and warm saline.

03:31.979 --> 03:34.246
Jesse: Got it.
Warm saline, guys. Come on!

03:34.248 --> 03:35.547
Come on, we need some blankets
in here.

03:35.549 --> 03:36.782
His temp is in the 80s,
Dr. Savetti.

03:36.784 --> 03:38.283
He needs active warming,
not a blanket.

03:38.285 --> 03:39.785
Here.

03:39.787 --> 03:41.553
We need to flood
his heart and lungs

03:41.555 --> 03:42.688
with everything we've got.

03:42.690 --> 03:45.958
Core temp... 82.
No heart rate.

03:45.960 --> 03:47.826
How long were compressions going
on in the field?

03:47.828 --> 03:49.712
At least 30 minutes.

03:49.713 --> 03:51.597
We were waiting to call
time of death till we got here.

03:51.599 --> 03:53.699
9...10...
Mario: Scalpel.

03:53.701 --> 03:56.935
Dr. Rorish, we've already done
eight rounds of acls,

03:56.937 --> 03:58.837
another 10 minutes of cpr.

03:58.839 --> 04:01.607
You can each do
six minute cpr shifts.

04:01.609 --> 04:02.841
That's 10 an hour.

04:02.843 --> 04:04.910
An hour of cpr?
Two, if necessary.

04:04.912 --> 04:07.546
Don't stop until that number
is in the mid-90s.

04:07.548 --> 04:09.648
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]
You are the heart now.

04:09.650 --> 04:12.951
All we know for sure right now
is that he's frozen.

04:14.855 --> 04:16.895
Bottom line, he's not dead
until he's warm and dead.

04:39.280 --> 04:40.712
[ Sighs ]
Your turn.

04:40.714 --> 04:42.214
[ Alarm beeping ]
[ Panting ]

04:42.215 --> 04:43.715
This must be what's it like
to go to the gym.

04:43.717 --> 04:45.450
Wow.
Look at this.

04:45.452 --> 04:46.985
What is that?

04:48.722 --> 04:50.789
Oh, I think
it's an engagement ring.

04:50.791 --> 04:52.424
Look at that.
Oh, my God.

04:52.426 --> 04:53.792
He was gonna ask her
to marry him?

04:53.794 --> 04:55.694
- Oh, you don't know that.
- Of course I do.

04:55.696 --> 04:56.895
Should we tell her?
No.

04:58.299 --> 05:00.065
I mean,
I don't think he's gonna...

05:00.067 --> 05:01.667
Oh, my God.
We have to tell her.

05:01.669 --> 05:04.536
What if he was having
second thoughts, huh?

05:04.538 --> 05:05.737
You know,
he was floating in the water,

05:05.739 --> 05:07.005
might have been
his last moments on earth.

05:07.007 --> 05:08.040
He didn't ask her then, right?

05:08.042 --> 05:09.741
Well, he was too busy drowning.

05:09.743 --> 05:11.777
I... you are
the least romantic person

05:11.779 --> 05:14.859
I have ever met in my life!
You can't propose to a girl
for someone else, okay?

05:15.849 --> 05:17.316
Listen.

05:17.318 --> 05:19.951
[ Monitors beeping ]

05:19.953 --> 05:22.487
His temp
is in the mid-90s.

05:24.391 --> 05:25.824
His pulses are strong.

05:25.826 --> 05:27.826
Good pupillary response.

05:27.828 --> 05:29.795
[ Laughs ]
Yeah!

05:29.797 --> 05:31.930
Dr. Rorish,
we have a got a live one.

05:31.932 --> 05:33.432
You can stop celebrating,
please.

05:33.434 --> 05:34.766
Blood pressure's 60 over 40.

05:34.768 --> 05:37.969
There you go.
You're ignoring the first rule.

05:37.971 --> 05:40.072
Make no assumptions.

05:40.074 --> 05:43.842
There's more...
There's always more.

05:43.844 --> 05:45.777
Let's get a fast ultrasound,
please.

05:45.779 --> 05:47.679
He could have underlying trauma
from the boat capsizing.

05:47.681 --> 05:50.082
Uh, who saw this...

05:50.084 --> 05:51.717
A bruise on the upper quadrant?

05:51.719 --> 05:53.452
No one?

05:53.454 --> 05:54.986
Great.
You skipped the exam.

05:54.988 --> 05:56.455
That's monitor syndrome.

05:56.457 --> 05:58.390
We don't rely on machines
in here.

05:58.392 --> 05:59.991
We use our eyes and our hands.

05:59.993 --> 06:01.760
This here is indicative
of bleeding.

06:01.762 --> 06:02.762
What do you see?

06:02.763 --> 06:06.131
Chest clear,
right abdomen clear,

06:06.133 --> 06:09.134
left abdomen... Blood.

06:09.136 --> 06:11.403
All right.
Let's increase fluids.

06:11.405 --> 06:12.871
One liter wide open,
2 units of blood.

06:12.873 --> 06:15.507
This could be
a splenic laceration.

06:15.509 --> 06:18.410
Why is that something we didn't
want to miss, Dr. Leighton?

06:18.412 --> 06:19.912
It can cause
life-threatening bleeding

06:19.913 --> 06:21.413
and particularly,
can worsen over time.
Exactly.

06:21.415 --> 06:24.816
So let's get a scan.
Someone page a surgeon.

06:24.818 --> 06:26.818
Mark my words...
He's gonna need an O.R.

06:27.955 --> 06:29.621
I need to ask you
what year it is.

06:29.623 --> 06:30.889
When can I see Killian?

06:30.891 --> 06:32.758
I honestly don't know.

06:34.895 --> 06:36.561
Can you tell me where you are?

06:36.563 --> 06:38.163
He wanted to do
something special.

06:38.165 --> 06:39.598
He sailed his whole life.

06:39.600 --> 06:41.566
He wasn't worried
about the weather.

06:43.637 --> 06:44.903
[ Voice breaking ]
He's dead, isn't he?

06:44.905 --> 06:47.906
Neal: Hello, Sophie.
I'm Dr. Hudson.

06:47.908 --> 06:50.776
I don't imagine
you remember me.
No.

06:50.778 --> 06:51.778
Well, I remember you.

06:51.779 --> 06:53.578
Clocked me pretty good
in the face.

06:53.580 --> 06:55.847
Malaya:
Her neuro exam was normal.

06:55.849 --> 06:57.916
Good.
You look a lot better.

06:57.918 --> 07:01.820
Sophie, you've got a displaced
fracture of your femur.

07:01.822 --> 07:04.122
It's very important that you
cooperate with us and don't...

07:04.124 --> 07:06.091
He saved my life.

07:06.092 --> 07:08.059
He got banged around
when the boat capsized,

07:08.061 --> 07:10.362
but still he made sure

07:10.363 --> 07:12.664
I was on top of the hull
out of the water.

07:12.666 --> 07:14.766
He couldn't climb up to me,

07:14.768 --> 07:18.069
so I held his hand
as he floated right under me.

07:18.071 --> 07:22.174
He stopped talking,
and I thought he was...

07:22.176 --> 07:23.475
Is he dead?

07:23.477 --> 07:26.111
No.
He's still fighting, okay?

07:26.113 --> 07:27.879
¶¶

07:32.686 --> 07:33.785
[ sighs ]

07:37.958 --> 07:39.791
Hi.
How many people so far?

07:39.793 --> 07:40.793
64.

07:40.794 --> 07:42.627
Really?
That's great.

07:42.629 --> 07:44.563
Make that 65.

07:44.565 --> 07:46.465
Thank for you doing this, Angus.

07:46.467 --> 07:49.234
Nothing says "I love you"
like a bone marrow drive.

07:49.236 --> 07:50.936
How's Carla doing?

07:50.938 --> 07:53.004
Carla's not the best patient.

07:53.006 --> 07:56.575
Well, she's a doctor.
We're all terrible patients.

07:56.577 --> 07:59.778
You told her
you were doing this, right?

08:01.548 --> 08:02.981
It wouldn't be happening, then.

08:02.983 --> 08:05.250
Malaya, I know
you're trying to help her,

08:05.252 --> 08:07.586
but maybe it's not the best idea
to just push this on her.

08:07.588 --> 08:09.888
But she's refusing treatment.
What am I supposed to do?

08:09.890 --> 08:11.890
But you can't force her
to choose between...

08:11.892 --> 08:13.492
Just drop it, okay?
She's pregnant.

08:13.494 --> 08:15.126
It's a very complicated
situation she's in.

08:15.128 --> 08:18.129
She's killing herself, Angus.

08:18.131 --> 08:20.432
I understand.

08:20.433 --> 08:22.734
It's just if I were Carla,
I would be really pissed off

08:22.736 --> 08:24.870
if I found out you were doing
all of this behind my back.

08:24.872 --> 08:28.273
I'll tell when it's over,
when maybe we found a match,

08:28.275 --> 08:30.842
when I can show her that
she still has a chance at life.

08:33.747 --> 08:37.282
If you don't want to do this,
okay, fine. Just leave.

08:37.284 --> 08:39.784
No, hey, calm down.

08:39.786 --> 08:41.253
I am here.

08:42.756 --> 08:44.990
I'm sorry.
[ Chuckling ] It's okay.

08:44.992 --> 08:46.625
[ Sighs ]

08:46.627 --> 08:49.294
You watch.

08:49.296 --> 08:52.297
I am gonna be a match.

08:54.067 --> 08:57.836
Never won the lotto,
but I'm gonna win this.

09:00.674 --> 09:03.909
[ Laughs ]

09:03.911 --> 09:05.710
Medics, report, please.

09:05.712 --> 09:08.747
38-year-old female transfer
from venice community hospital.

09:08.749 --> 09:10.682
Auto collision.
Mom here was the driver.

09:10.684 --> 09:12.117
Some neck stiffness.
Kid was cleared.

09:12.119 --> 09:13.818
Why the transfer?
It seemed minor.

09:13.820 --> 09:15.370
Venice isn't a trauma center.

09:15.371 --> 09:16.921
Did the other doctors explain
why they sent you here?

09:16.924 --> 09:18.790
No, but they ruined
our vacation.

09:18.792 --> 09:20.191
Randell, please.

09:20.193 --> 09:22.394
Someone just plowed
right into us.

09:22.395 --> 09:24.715
You guys don't seem to handle
the rain very well down here.

09:28.335 --> 09:29.901
Ooh.
What... what are you doing?

09:29.903 --> 09:31.369
I need a c-collar

09:31.370 --> 09:32.836
and a neuro icu bed,
please, right away.

09:32.839 --> 09:34.673
Mom?
It's okay, honey.

09:34.675 --> 09:36.141
The hospital they sent you to
scanned your neck,

09:36.143 --> 09:37.343
but it appears

09:37.344 --> 09:38.544
I'm the first and only doctor
to read the results.

09:38.545 --> 09:39.745
And... and it's bad?

09:39.746 --> 09:40.946
You have a cervical fracture.

09:40.947 --> 09:42.147
You need a fixation device
called a halo to fix it.

09:42.149 --> 09:43.915
You got it?
I told you they were
some cheap doc-in-a-box.

09:43.917 --> 09:45.216
Randell, stop.

09:45.218 --> 09:46.985
You're gonna need surgery
tonight, Rebecca.

09:46.987 --> 09:48.353
Wait!
What about my son?

09:48.355 --> 09:50.789
There's no one here with us.
His father's in Portland.

09:50.791 --> 09:52.290
Mom, do we have to stay here?

09:52.292 --> 09:54.593
Uh, Dr. Taylor.

09:54.595 --> 09:56.027
Some back-up in here,
please.

09:56.029 --> 09:58.296
- Can you page social work?
- I don't want a social worker.

09:58.298 --> 09:59.965
It'll be tough to get one
in code red.

09:59.967 --> 10:01.132
Well,
her husband's out of state.

10:01.134 --> 10:03.635
Ex-husband.
They're getting divorced.

10:03.637 --> 10:05.870
[ Code bag beeping ]

10:05.872 --> 10:08.173
Ugh, that's the code bag.
I got to go.

10:08.175 --> 10:09.841
You're gonna have to say goodbye
to your mom for a little while.

10:09.843 --> 10:12.711
Okay? Don't lose that icu bed.
Take her upstairs now.

10:12.713 --> 10:15.914
Dr. Taylor.
Can you handle the boy?

10:15.916 --> 10:17.816
Absolutely not.
He's just kidding.

10:17.818 --> 10:18.818
I got to go.

10:18.819 --> 10:19.985
Wha...

10:19.987 --> 10:22.287
Be good, randell. Okay?
I'll see you soon.

10:22.289 --> 10:24.789
Thank you for doing this!

10:24.791 --> 10:27.125
Um...

10:28.829 --> 10:32.130
Wow.
This is, uh... this is awkward.

10:32.132 --> 10:35.333
Will you take me
to grauman's Chinese?

10:35.335 --> 10:36.768
That's where we were headed.

10:36.770 --> 10:38.703
I'm working.

10:38.705 --> 10:40.071
Do you have any idea
what a job is?

10:40.073 --> 10:41.339
Have you ever, you know,

10:41.341 --> 10:42.941
raked leaves
or had a paper route?

10:42.943 --> 10:44.409
What's a paper route?

10:44.411 --> 10:47.345
God, I'm old.
All right.

10:47.347 --> 10:50.015
You just follow me
and make sure you don't look

10:50.017 --> 10:52.117
at any of the gory stuff,
all right?

10:52.119 --> 10:53.952
Come on.
Stay close.

10:53.954 --> 10:56.388
Are you kidding me?
We both have to sign
just to get him a scan?

10:56.390 --> 10:58.089
It's a double doc.
What can I tell you?

10:58.091 --> 11:02.961
Sign there, there, and there.

11:02.963 --> 11:04.262
Hello.
Remember me?

11:04.264 --> 11:05.797
Just a second,
Mr. banks.

11:05.799 --> 11:06.831
Hey, do you still have
that ring?

11:06.833 --> 11:08.466
What ring?

11:08.467 --> 11:10.100
Oh, my God. These two kids
came in earlier today.

11:10.103 --> 11:12.103
Uh, did you ever see
the last scene in "Titanic"?

11:12.105 --> 11:13.371
Malaya said
that's what happened out there.

11:13.373 --> 11:15.740
Sorry.
I've never seen that movie.

11:15.741 --> 11:18.108
What?
Kate winslet holding
Leonardo DiCaprio's hand

11:18.111 --> 11:20.211
as he floats in the water,
dying.

11:20.213 --> 11:22.113
Yeah, so she can stay
on the raft and live.

11:22.115 --> 11:23.582
Absolutely amazing, right?

11:23.583 --> 11:25.050
That raft was big enough
for both of them,

11:25.052 --> 11:26.951
just so you know.
No, don't say that.
That's wrong.

11:26.953 --> 11:28.119
Okay, you know what?

11:28.121 --> 11:29.988
We just brought our Leo
back to life.

11:29.990 --> 11:31.289
All right, gentlemen.
What do you got?

11:31.291 --> 11:33.692
Me.
You've got me.
64-year-old man

11:33.694 --> 11:35.694
we brought in
from the waiting room...
why don't you say that
a little louder

11:35.696 --> 11:36.861
so everyone can hear?

11:36.863 --> 11:38.396
Hello, I'm Dr. Guthrie.

11:38.398 --> 11:40.231
Ted banks.
It's nice to meet you.

11:40.233 --> 11:42.000
Mario:
He's complaining of fatigue.

11:42.002 --> 11:45.070
I said exhaustion, not fatigue.

11:45.072 --> 11:47.372
Blood pressure's normal.

11:47.374 --> 11:50.008
Hmm.
Well, you sound fine.

11:50.010 --> 11:51.409
So what brings you in today,
Mr. banks?

11:51.411 --> 11:57.182
I've been having these spells
when I feel bone tired.

11:57.184 --> 11:59.417
It's hard just getting
across the room sometimes.

11:59.419 --> 12:00.885
Anything else that you noticed?

12:00.887 --> 12:02.454
Any fevers, chills,
shortness of breath?

12:02.456 --> 12:06.725
Shortness of breath,
but just sometimes.

12:06.727 --> 12:08.460
I'm always honest
on the first date.

12:08.462 --> 12:09.427
I'm HIV-positive.

12:09.429 --> 12:10.895
Ooh, for how long?

12:10.897 --> 12:13.198
Since the Reagan administration.

12:13.200 --> 12:14.432
You're a survivor.

12:14.434 --> 12:16.034
I am nothing if not that.

12:16.036 --> 12:18.803
Let's draw labs
on this lovely gentleman.

12:18.805 --> 12:20.171
It's wonderful to meet you, Ted.

12:20.173 --> 12:21.906
You, as well.
Thank you.

12:21.908 --> 12:23.408
[ Clears throat ]

12:23.410 --> 12:25.110
What a nice man.

12:26.213 --> 12:28.079
What's your name again,
sweetheart?

12:28.081 --> 12:29.380
Me?
[ Chuckles ]

12:29.382 --> 12:30.482
Dr. Savetti.

12:30.484 --> 12:32.250
Right.
And you?

12:32.252 --> 12:35.120
Um,
I'm Dr. Leighton.

12:38.091 --> 12:39.958
You guys aren't a thing,
are you?

12:39.960 --> 12:41.493
No.
No.

12:42.529 --> 12:44.929
I'll go ahead
and get his labs.
Yep.

12:44.931 --> 12:47.031
Okay.

12:47.033 --> 12:49.934
And here I go
to the glue factory.

12:49.936 --> 12:51.936
[ Laughs ]

12:51.938 --> 12:53.805
[ Monitors beeping rapidly ]
If you...

12:53.807 --> 12:55.240
This is it.
Come on in.

12:55.242 --> 12:57.075
We pushed some versed,
and he's not responsive.

12:57.077 --> 12:58.309
Not responsive?
He's not breathing.

12:58.311 --> 12:59.878
This was just a routine
skin biopsy.

12:59.880 --> 13:01.946
This is v-tach.
It's a shockable rhythm.

13:01.948 --> 13:04.315
¶¶

13:04.317 --> 13:07.051
[ paddles whine ]
Clear.

13:07.053 --> 13:08.219
[ Thump ]

13:08.221 --> 13:09.287
[ Beeping slows ]

13:09.289 --> 13:11.856
There.
Back to normal.

13:11.858 --> 13:14.559
Wonderful.
Thank you.

13:14.561 --> 13:18.229
He'll need a stat EKG
and an icu bed,

13:18.231 --> 13:19.564
but the worst is over.

13:21.501 --> 13:24.102
So I'm just curious.

13:24.104 --> 13:26.437
Dermatologists really don't know
how to use a defibrillator?

13:26.439 --> 13:29.374
I haven't done cpr in 20 years.

13:29.376 --> 13:31.976
Policy is to call the code bag.

13:31.978 --> 13:35.213
Hmm.
Glad to be of help.

13:38.585 --> 13:40.352
[ Knock on door ]

13:40.353 --> 13:42.120
Why isn't Killian wahler
getting an O.R.?

13:42.122 --> 13:44.155
His scan shows
a grade 4 splenic laceration.

13:44.157 --> 13:46.057
It was a grade 2, at best.

13:46.059 --> 13:47.592
With cases like that,
we like to wait.

13:47.594 --> 13:49.127
They tend to get better
on their own.

13:49.129 --> 13:50.562
But I was just with him,
and you weren't.

13:50.564 --> 13:53.198
We keep giving him fluids.
He's not responding like I want.

13:54.601 --> 13:56.134
I've seen hundreds of these.

13:56.136 --> 13:57.602
You're undercalling it.
He needs the knife.

13:57.604 --> 13:59.604
I went down there, leanne.
I was with him.

13:59.606 --> 14:02.073
And you're right.
His exam was unimpressive.

14:02.075 --> 14:04.108
Vitals are stable.

14:04.110 --> 14:05.610
I'm sorry.

14:05.611 --> 14:07.111
It doesn't warrant
an immediate surgery.

14:07.113 --> 14:09.614
What happened to you
in San Francisco?

14:13.053 --> 14:14.452
Nothing happened
in San Francisco.

14:14.454 --> 14:15.987
Doesn't sound like nothing.

14:15.989 --> 14:18.389
Can't we disagree without
impugning my integrity?

14:19.893 --> 14:22.126
Look,
I need to go to the O.R.

14:22.128 --> 14:24.963
Uh, close the door
when you're done.

14:26.600 --> 14:31.002
"Old age ain't for sissies."

14:31.004 --> 14:32.437
Who said that?

14:32.439 --> 14:34.405
Joan rivers.

14:34.407 --> 14:36.941
You really are an idiot,
aren't you? Bette Davis.

14:36.943 --> 14:38.309
Please tell me you know
who that is.

14:38.311 --> 14:40.445
She was on "golden girls",
right?

14:40.447 --> 14:42.180
[ Chuckles ]

14:43.917 --> 14:46.551
These gloves are the bane
of my existence.

14:46.553 --> 14:49.053
You do know that what I have
is bloodborne, right?

14:49.055 --> 14:50.188
It's fine.
Can you try?

14:50.190 --> 14:52.123
I'm on it.

14:52.124 --> 14:54.057
So, if you two aren't together,
who you with?

14:54.060 --> 14:56.494
Oh, for him, it depends
on what day of the week it is.

14:56.496 --> 14:57.428
Shut up.
[ Chuckles ]

14:57.430 --> 14:59.297
Big man on campus, huh?

14:59.299 --> 15:02.066
He would like to think so.

15:06.072 --> 15:07.505
Just about done.

15:10.310 --> 15:14.679
¶¶

15:17.617 --> 15:18.817
Did you get it?
Yeah. All good.

15:37.170 --> 15:40.505
Bitch. It's bitch.
I'm in the emergency room.

15:40.507 --> 15:41.639
I forgot to feed the cat.

15:41.641 --> 15:43.942
If you're in town, call me.

15:43.944 --> 15:46.144
I hear you're feeling
a little worse.

15:46.146 --> 15:48.112
I'm kind of glad.

15:48.114 --> 15:51.215
It's like when you take
your car to the shop,

15:51.217 --> 15:53.418
it never does
what it does at home.

15:53.420 --> 15:54.703
52.

15:54.704 --> 15:55.987
Your heart rate's a little low.

15:55.989 --> 15:57.388
What does my bloodwork say?

15:57.390 --> 15:58.556
Hasn't come back yet.

15:58.558 --> 16:00.992
What does yours say?

16:00.994 --> 16:01.994
Excuse me?

16:01.995 --> 16:04.095
You got stuck, didn't you?

16:04.097 --> 16:07.332
What are you gonna do about it?

16:07.334 --> 16:09.267
I'm not gonna enter it into
the system, that's for sure.

16:09.269 --> 16:10.601
I'd have mounds of paperwork
to fill out.

16:10.603 --> 16:12.270
I'm gonna put you
on a temporary pacemaker

16:12.272 --> 16:13.671
to see if we can get
your heart rate up.

16:13.673 --> 16:15.373
You're pretty cavalier
about this.

16:15.375 --> 16:17.008
It's low blood pressure.
It's nothing to worry about.

16:17.010 --> 16:18.476
I'm not talking about me.

16:20.013 --> 16:21.679
I'll be fine. All right?
Don't worry about it.

16:21.681 --> 16:25.483
You should pop a few truvada
just in case.

16:25.485 --> 16:27.552
It's what all the boys do now,
right?

16:27.554 --> 16:29.354
And after they're done
tomcatting around,

16:29.356 --> 16:32.657
my, oh my God,
the weddings and the surrogates.

16:32.659 --> 16:34.392
If I see another Facebook photo

16:34.394 --> 16:39.564
of Jackson or Emma's
first day of kindergarten...

16:39.566 --> 16:42.133
You know what it was like
when I was growing up in Ohio

16:42.135 --> 16:44.035
during the middle ages?

16:44.037 --> 16:47.405
They called it the love
that dare not speak its name.

16:47.407 --> 16:48.706
[ Sighs ]

16:48.708 --> 16:51.442
Who said that?
I have no idea.

16:51.444 --> 16:53.778
Oscar wilde.

16:54.748 --> 16:56.547
You're not mad at me, are you?

16:56.549 --> 16:57.715
Why would I be mad at you?

16:57.717 --> 16:59.250
I don't know.

16:59.252 --> 17:01.019
I screwed
half the San Fernando valley,

17:01.021 --> 17:02.453
and I just had
a rotary telephone.

17:02.455 --> 17:03.755
Imagine what I could have done

17:03.757 --> 17:06.057
with all the apps
you kids have today.

17:06.059 --> 17:08.092
Well, if you weren't careful,
that's your business.

17:08.094 --> 17:09.794
See?
You are mad at me.

17:09.796 --> 17:13.664
First of all, we didn't know.

17:13.666 --> 17:15.199
And even if we did,

17:15.200 --> 17:16.733
are you telling me
you never went out

17:16.736 --> 17:19.037
and did something
you regretted the next day?

17:19.039 --> 17:20.155
You never made a mistake?

17:20.156 --> 17:21.272
I'm careful,
if that's what you mean.

17:21.274 --> 17:22.507
You weren't a little while ago,

17:22.509 --> 17:24.075
or we wouldn't
be talking about this.

17:24.077 --> 17:25.343
We're gonna have to monitor you
for a little bit.

17:25.345 --> 17:26.677
If you want to call someone,
have them come down...

17:26.679 --> 17:29.347
All my friends are either dead
or in palm Springs.

17:29.349 --> 17:31.215
I'll check on you
in a little bit.

17:31.217 --> 17:32.650
Bye!

17:32.652 --> 17:34.786
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

17:34.788 --> 17:36.621
What's going on?

17:36.623 --> 17:37.622
Jesse: Killian's
blood pressure's tanking.

17:37.624 --> 17:39.090
He's lost consciousness.
Damn it.

17:39.092 --> 17:40.092
I need an attending!

17:40.093 --> 17:41.492
I already gave him two boluses.

17:41.494 --> 17:42.827
Give him two more.
I'll start another line.

17:42.829 --> 17:44.128
Okay.
What do you got?

17:44.130 --> 17:45.530
We got a lot of blood.

17:45.532 --> 17:47.399
Yeah, I'm not surprised.

17:47.400 --> 17:49.267
This is what happens with
a high-grade splenic laceration.

17:49.269 --> 17:50.768
You've got fluids.
Is blood coming in?

17:50.770 --> 17:52.770
18 going in now.
Four lines.

17:52.772 --> 17:54.572
I need an O.R. right now.

17:54.574 --> 17:56.641
Not gonna happen, leanne.
We're in code black.

17:56.643 --> 17:58.509
This guy has about two hours
left to live.

17:58.511 --> 17:59.710
I didn't raise him up
from the dead

17:59.712 --> 18:01.145
just to see him die
all over again.

18:01.147 --> 18:02.647
Let's get him to center stage,
mama.

18:02.649 --> 18:03.649
Jesse: Let's go.

18:03.650 --> 18:05.650
¶¶

18:05.652 --> 18:07.085
What's going on now?

18:07.087 --> 18:08.853
Excrement just made
physical contact

18:08.855 --> 18:11.289
with an air current
distribution device, kid.

18:11.291 --> 18:12.790
Page Dr. Cole Guthrie.

18:12.792 --> 18:15.193
Tell him I was right.
He'll know what you mean.

18:15.195 --> 18:17.462
Hey, don't worry.

18:17.463 --> 18:19.730
These people have
super-human powers, all right?

18:19.732 --> 18:22.300
Trust me.
Come here.

18:23.503 --> 18:25.103
Mario:
Hey, this is Dr. Angus Leighton.

18:25.105 --> 18:31.843
My DEA number is cdx608325.

18:31.845 --> 18:37.115
Truvada,
200mg/300mg qd for 30 tabs.

18:37.117 --> 18:39.283
One refill.
How soon can it be ready?

18:39.285 --> 18:40.285
Okay, thanks.

18:40.286 --> 18:42.353
[ Cellphone beeps ]

18:44.624 --> 18:46.624
[ Sighs ]

18:52.365 --> 18:54.565
What are you doing?
God, you scared me.

18:54.567 --> 18:56.300
Risa told me where you were.

18:56.302 --> 18:57.668
We ran out of airway kits.

18:57.670 --> 19:00.238
You should be home in bed.

19:00.240 --> 19:02.440
You're having
a bone marrow drive?

19:02.442 --> 19:04.609
I've gotten like five e-mails
wishing me well.

19:04.611 --> 19:06.677
[ Sighs ]
I can't talk about this now.

19:06.679 --> 19:08.412
Okay.

19:08.414 --> 19:10.448
And you're handing...
You're handing out flyers.

19:10.450 --> 19:12.534
I mean, this is so you.

19:12.535 --> 19:14.619
This is so you to try
and bake sale away leukemia.

19:14.621 --> 19:16.404
You know what, Carla?

19:16.405 --> 19:18.188
Over 70 people have taken time
out of their insane night

19:18.191 --> 19:19.191
to try and help you.

19:19.192 --> 19:20.591
No, I don't want their help.

19:20.593 --> 19:22.493
I know
it's a hard decision...
no, it's not.

19:22.495 --> 19:24.362
But the one thing you can't do
is nothing.

19:24.364 --> 19:26.397
Nothing gets me a healthy baby.

19:26.399 --> 19:28.166
Treatment gets me a 6% chance

19:28.168 --> 19:29.867
of being alive
after three years.

19:29.869 --> 19:32.303
The survival rate can be higher.

19:32.305 --> 19:33.638
They're trialing
new approaches...

19:33.640 --> 19:35.473
Aerosolized gm-csf...

19:35.475 --> 19:37.441
No, I'm not... I'm not
gonna induce at 24 weeks

19:37.443 --> 19:38.609
for a 6% chance.

19:38.611 --> 19:39.710
24 weeks is doable.

19:39.712 --> 19:41.078
Doable?

19:41.079 --> 19:42.445
Do you think
that being born blue

19:42.448 --> 19:44.815
and having to be intubated
is doable?

19:44.817 --> 19:46.817
You think
being in the nicu for months

19:46.819 --> 19:49.754
and then even if it survives,
ending up with cerebral palsy

19:49.756 --> 19:51.022
or lung disease

19:51.023 --> 19:52.289
or an intraventricular
hemorrhage.

19:52.292 --> 19:53.808
You think that's doable?

19:53.809 --> 19:55.325
I'm sorry, but to me,
that is not doable.

19:55.328 --> 19:58.596
I'm not gonna sit by
and watch you die.

19:58.598 --> 19:59.964
That's not doable, either.

20:02.202 --> 20:03.768
I thought
for whatever time I had left

20:03.770 --> 20:05.436
that you were back in my life.

20:06.639 --> 20:09.707
I guess not.

20:09.709 --> 20:11.776
[ Door opens ]

20:16.649 --> 20:18.416
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]
Leanne: Go! Let's go!
I need the spot.

20:18.418 --> 20:19.617
Bring it in.

20:20.887 --> 20:22.287
Okay, I was wrong.

20:22.288 --> 20:23.688
Well, what are we gonna do
about it?

20:23.690 --> 20:25.690
We're going to take
his spleen out.

20:26.893 --> 20:28.960
You. You.
I need six units of... what?

20:28.962 --> 20:30.294
A-positive.
And a bovie.

20:30.296 --> 20:32.847
Yes, doctor.

20:32.848 --> 20:35.399
What are you doing?
There's no blood in there.
I'm sorry.
It's policy.

20:35.401 --> 20:36.901
I can't get it from the fridge
until I get an order.

20:36.902 --> 20:38.402
There's no time.
That's the only policy
you need to know about.

20:38.404 --> 20:40.238
Look, I'm new here.
I just have to log in...

20:40.240 --> 20:42.506
Okay, I'm new here, too.
Here's how I log in.

20:43.710 --> 20:45.276
[ Glass shatters ]

20:51.985 --> 20:54.819
I'll be right back
with the blood.

20:57.991 --> 21:00.258
What, you never threw
a computer?

21:00.260 --> 21:03.294
Oh, I threw one once...
Through a plate glass window.

21:03.296 --> 21:04.362
Does that count?

21:13.806 --> 21:15.156
Oh.
Oh, hold up.

21:15.157 --> 21:16.507
Can you, uh,
reach in the pocket there?

21:16.509 --> 21:18.743
Grab the phone and the speaker.

21:18.745 --> 21:20.544
I always listen to music
while I operate.

21:23.449 --> 21:24.515
Hold on, Kim.

21:25.752 --> 21:27.685
Are you gonna
apologize to her first?

21:27.687 --> 21:29.787
I don't care about the computer.

21:29.789 --> 21:33.291
I just don't like people
talking to my nurses that way.

21:35.662 --> 21:36.894
Right.
I understand.

21:36.896 --> 21:40.731
Uh, I'm very sorry, Kim.

21:43.069 --> 21:44.869
You know, that's my second
apology today.

21:44.871 --> 21:46.504
I'm well aware of that.

21:46.506 --> 21:48.739
Scalpel.
Retractor.

21:48.741 --> 21:52.310
You. Hold the retractor,
and suction in the other hand.

21:53.646 --> 21:55.313
And you pick a song.

21:55.315 --> 21:57.882
I got anything you want.
I'll pass.

21:57.884 --> 21:59.467
Okay. I'll pick.

21:59.468 --> 22:01.051
Play Dan the automator,
"bang the ball".

22:01.054 --> 22:03.654
And bovie, please.

22:03.656 --> 22:05.690
[ "Bang the ball" plays ]

22:05.692 --> 22:07.058
4-0 silk.
Right here.

22:07.060 --> 22:10.061
¶ You already know what it is,
man ¶

22:10.063 --> 22:12.330
[ music continues in distance ]

22:13.766 --> 22:15.066
Sophie.

22:15.068 --> 22:16.251
Sophie, no.
You have to lie down.

22:16.252 --> 22:17.435
What's going on?
Is he all right?

22:17.437 --> 22:18.769
You have...
You have to lie down.

22:18.771 --> 22:20.671
I heard them talking.
He's being operated on.

22:20.673 --> 22:22.606
Where?
You need to go back
to your gurney?

22:22.608 --> 22:24.809
[ Groans ]
Where is he?
Sophie, stop.

22:24.811 --> 22:27.678
[ Groans ] He's in there
with the music, isn't he?

22:27.680 --> 22:30.948
Sophie, I'm gonna put you
on this gurney.

22:30.950 --> 22:33.818
I'll park it
right outside, okay?

22:33.820 --> 22:35.353
[ Groans ]

22:35.355 --> 22:37.088
But you have to lie down.

22:37.090 --> 22:38.889
Okay.

22:41.961 --> 22:44.895
I know you love him
and you want to help,

22:44.897 --> 22:47.498
but you have to take care
of yourself, too.

22:47.500 --> 22:49.567
[ Music continues ]

22:52.705 --> 22:55.106
¶ You can see it in my soul
when I take it to the hole ¶

22:55.108 --> 22:56.807
¶ and I dunk like that ¶

22:56.809 --> 22:58.843
¶ unh,
you can see it in my stride... ¶

22:58.845 --> 23:01.445
what's his heart rate?
In the 30s.

23:01.447 --> 23:02.813
His heart block's worsening.

23:02.815 --> 23:04.582
Dr. Savetti, explain.

23:04.584 --> 23:06.984
He seemed fine.
Third-degree heart block.

23:06.986 --> 23:08.719
I put him on pacer pads.

23:08.721 --> 23:10.755
Looks like he's progressed
to complete heart block now.

23:10.757 --> 23:12.456
This doesn't sound good.

23:12.458 --> 23:14.458
Heart arrhythmias
can take a turn.

23:14.460 --> 23:16.727
Is this the plague
coming back to bite me?

23:16.729 --> 23:20.164
Because I have been
one compliant patient.

23:20.166 --> 23:21.966
No, it's just your heart.

23:21.968 --> 23:24.135
It's not working optimally
anymore, Ted.

23:24.137 --> 23:26.003
You're getting older.

23:26.005 --> 23:27.104
Wow.

23:27.106 --> 23:28.739
I've actually lived long enough

23:28.741 --> 23:31.442
to die of something
other than aids.

23:31.444 --> 23:33.944
That's a dark victory, huh?

23:33.946 --> 23:36.046
I'm gonna increase
the voltage on these pads.

23:36.048 --> 23:37.481
It's gonna hurt a little bit.

23:37.483 --> 23:40.151
"Ann, there's a storm coming."

23:40.153 --> 23:43.087
It's been raining
for a while, Ted.

23:43.088 --> 23:46.022
"Oh, it'll rain cats and dogs
and ruin all our nice bulbs."

23:46.025 --> 23:48.659
He has no idea
what film this is from, Ted.

23:48.661 --> 23:49.994
"I can still feel
the sun on my hands."

23:49.996 --> 23:51.962
[ Device whines ]
You ready?

23:51.964 --> 23:52.897
If I don't make it...

23:52.899 --> 23:53.899
[ thump ]
[ Groans ]

23:53.900 --> 23:56.967
Can you call a friend for me?

23:56.969 --> 23:58.903
We call each other bitch...
[ Groans ]

23:58.905 --> 24:02.873
But his real name is Bruce.
It's in my contacts.

24:02.875 --> 24:05.843
I've left a couple messages.
He's not calling me back.

24:05.845 --> 24:09.547
[ Groans ]
Someone's got to feed my cat.

24:09.549 --> 24:10.948
Rollie: All right.

24:10.950 --> 24:12.783
We're gonna start
the transvenous pacing now.

24:15.121 --> 24:19.190
Hey, uh, what movie
was that from, anyway?

24:19.192 --> 24:22.660
"Dark victory", honey.

24:22.662 --> 24:25.162
[ Exhales sharply ]
"Dark victory."

24:25.164 --> 24:26.764
¶ Yeah, yeah ¶ okay, all right.

24:26.766 --> 24:29.133
Clamp, please.
Leanne: Right here.

24:29.135 --> 24:30.734
Mind if I change the station?

24:30.736 --> 24:32.670
Yeah, go for it.

24:32.671 --> 24:34.605
[ "Bang the ball" continues
indistinctly ]

24:34.607 --> 24:36.640
The who.
"Live at Leeds".

24:36.642 --> 24:38.108
I never heard of them.

24:38.110 --> 24:40.644
You've never hear of the who?

24:40.646 --> 24:42.263
"Magic bus"?

24:42.264 --> 24:43.881
Oh, no. I know that song...
White people music.

24:43.883 --> 24:44.949
[ Laughs ]
Bovie.

24:44.951 --> 24:47.485
Bovie, please.
Bovie. Suction.

24:47.487 --> 24:48.803
Leanne:
I listen to Stevie wonder,

24:48.804 --> 24:50.120
and I don't call it
black people music.
Suction.

24:50.122 --> 24:51.555
Well, you should.

24:51.557 --> 24:54.124
See, we don't get credit
for anything.

24:54.126 --> 24:55.593
4-0, please.

24:55.595 --> 24:59.063
Suction, please.
Angus, pull harder.

24:59.065 --> 25:00.865
Mama, curved Kelly, please.

25:00.867 --> 25:02.266
Here you go, daddy.

25:02.268 --> 25:03.567
Mama? Daddy?

25:03.569 --> 25:05.836
What is up with that?
It's a long story.

25:05.838 --> 25:07.104
Angus.

25:07.106 --> 25:08.606
Retract harder.
What's wrong with you?

25:08.608 --> 25:10.941
You are tough.

25:10.943 --> 25:11.842
Daddy.

25:11.844 --> 25:14.745
Not as tough as this artery.

25:14.747 --> 25:16.547
BP's coming up.

25:16.549 --> 25:17.815
Angus: Phew!
Just in time.

25:17.817 --> 25:19.783
We were about a liter down.

25:21.254 --> 25:23.120
[ Pager beeps ]
Uh, one more suture.

25:23.122 --> 25:24.221
Ah, damn it.
I'm being paged.
Uh-oh.

25:24.223 --> 25:26.624
We done here?

25:26.626 --> 25:28.826
Okay, I'll be back to close up.

25:29.862 --> 25:32.263
Damn, that was hot.

25:37.970 --> 25:39.603
You're sweating.

25:39.605 --> 25:41.238
It's warm in here.

25:41.240 --> 25:43.207
It's 68 degrees in here.

25:44.277 --> 25:45.277
I'm just saying.

25:47.647 --> 25:49.280
You heard the man.
Prep for closure.

25:49.282 --> 25:51.849
Uh-huh.
[ Chuckles ]

25:55.021 --> 25:56.654
Is he gonna be okay?

25:57.823 --> 26:01.725
You're Sophie.
Killian's friend.

26:03.195 --> 26:07.331
Yes.
He should be just fine.

26:07.333 --> 26:10.000
Let's get her back to her room.

26:12.171 --> 26:14.638
Ted: What the hell
are you doing anyway?

26:14.640 --> 26:16.807
We're putting
a catheter into your vein

26:16.809 --> 26:18.208
right below
your right collarbone

26:18.210 --> 26:19.743
and snaking it to your heart

26:19.745 --> 26:21.278
to try to correct
your heart rhythm.

26:21.280 --> 26:24.148
It dances to its own drummer.

26:26.852 --> 26:28.919
All right, Dr. Savetti.

26:28.921 --> 26:30.721
You ready?

26:31.657 --> 26:34.191
Insert the pacing catheter
into the cordis

26:34.193 --> 26:37.294
and thread it
into his right ventricle.

26:37.296 --> 26:40.831
Good, good.
Easy.

26:40.833 --> 26:43.601
Let the EKG rhythm guide you.

26:43.603 --> 26:45.636
Once you've reached the heart,

26:45.638 --> 26:47.771
the pace will normalize
on its own.

26:47.773 --> 26:49.039
He's mad at me, you know.

26:49.041 --> 26:50.608
Would you stop saying that?

26:52.812 --> 26:56.680
"Ann, please understand."

26:56.682 --> 27:00.351
No one must be here.
No one.

27:00.353 --> 27:02.786
Be my best friend.

27:02.788 --> 27:05.122
"Go now, please."

27:06.959 --> 27:07.959
"Dark victory" again?

27:07.960 --> 27:10.928
Oh, yes.
The death scene.

27:10.930 --> 27:13.764
There.

27:13.766 --> 27:15.366
Good.

27:15.368 --> 27:17.801
[ Chuckles ]

27:17.803 --> 27:19.770
How are you feeling, Ted?

27:21.073 --> 27:22.306
Ted?

27:22.308 --> 27:24.041
Is he all right?

27:24.043 --> 27:27.244
Yeah, he's just sleeping.
We'll let him rest.

27:27.246 --> 27:30.781
[ Sighs ]
His generation of gay men...

27:30.783 --> 27:32.950
It's the end of an era,
you know?

27:32.952 --> 27:35.352
Got a lot of people
standing on their shoulders.

27:36.722 --> 27:39.089
Why are you mad at him?

27:39.091 --> 27:42.026
I'm not.

27:42.028 --> 27:44.428
I'm mad at myself.

27:46.999 --> 27:48.966
Don't you want to get
some sleep?

27:48.968 --> 27:50.901
It's 3:00 in the morning.

27:50.902 --> 27:52.835
I just blew up three cars
<i>and</i> got a hooker.

27:52.838 --> 27:54.138
I'm not going to bed now.

27:54.140 --> 27:57.074
Just checking.

27:58.244 --> 28:01.011
Got any kids or a wife?

28:01.013 --> 28:04.081
One wife, one kid.

28:05.284 --> 28:07.217
[<i> Gunfire, woman screams</i> ]

28:07.219 --> 28:08.686
Your parents getting divorced?

28:08.688 --> 28:09.753
I don't care.

28:09.755 --> 28:10.988
Look, don't be a liar, kid.

28:10.990 --> 28:12.756
My parents got divorced,
and I cared.

28:15.895 --> 28:17.161
What was it like?

28:17.163 --> 28:22.766
Well, they feel really guilty,

28:22.768 --> 28:25.335
so you can get a lot of stuff
if you play your cards right.

28:25.337 --> 28:27.171
That's cool.

28:27.173 --> 28:30.340
Yeah.

28:30.342 --> 28:34.845
But they still love you
just as much as they ever did.

28:37.950 --> 28:39.183
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]
I was paged.

28:39.185 --> 28:40.251
It's respiratory failure.

28:40.252 --> 28:41.318
Patient just came
back from the O.R.

28:41.320 --> 28:44.354
Rebecca?
Her sats are down to 76.

28:44.356 --> 28:46.223
What happened?

28:46.225 --> 28:49.727
Okay, I need suction now
and intubation meds drawn up.

28:49.729 --> 28:51.395
We don't intubate here.
That's why we called you.

28:51.397 --> 28:52.963
Can someone take that thing off?

28:52.965 --> 28:54.031
We can't.
Neuro has the key,

28:54.033 --> 28:55.533
and they haven't answered
my page.

28:55.534 --> 28:57.034
Look, I'll intubate her,
but I absolutely need

28:57.036 --> 28:58.469
the wrench to unlock
the halo to do it.

28:58.471 --> 28:59.970
I can't intubate
with that halo on.

28:59.972 --> 29:01.371
Can't we just
remove it manually?

29:01.373 --> 29:03.340
It's screwed into the bone.
I can't do it.

29:03.342 --> 29:05.109
Go find that wrench!

29:05.111 --> 29:08.045
[ Rebecca gasping ]

29:08.047 --> 29:10.147
Leanne: Sophie,
you're hyperventilating, okay?

29:10.149 --> 29:12.883
Breathe slowly
so that you don't pass out.

29:12.885 --> 29:13.984
What the hell happened?

29:13.986 --> 29:15.052
The skin is rock-hard tense.

29:15.054 --> 29:16.854
Might be
early compartment syndrome.

29:16.856 --> 29:18.288
No, it's too quick for that.

29:18.290 --> 29:20.324
This is blood I'm feeling,
not swelling.

29:20.326 --> 29:22.192
She has a mid-shaft
femur fracture.

29:22.194 --> 29:24.027
It must have sheared off the
vessels that run along the bone.

29:24.029 --> 29:25.963
Oh, that would explain
the blood pooling in her thigh.

29:25.965 --> 29:27.030
She got up to walk.

29:27.933 --> 29:29.149
Who let her do that?

29:29.150 --> 29:30.366
She was insisting
on finding her friend.

29:30.369 --> 29:32.002
Is she your doctor
or are you hers?

29:32.004 --> 29:33.303
I put her on a gurney
as soon as I could.

29:33.305 --> 29:34.938
And you left her
to watch center stage?

29:34.939 --> 29:36.572
What if she had gotten up
to move again?

29:36.573 --> 29:38.206
I'm sorry, but that was
the love of her life in there.

29:38.210 --> 29:40.310
And now she's the one
we have to save or
she loses her lower leg.

29:40.312 --> 29:42.379
No pulse down here. We have
to get this leg straight.

29:42.381 --> 29:43.714
She needs an emergent reduction.

29:43.715 --> 29:45.048
- Okay, Dr. Pineda, you with us?
- Yes.

29:45.050 --> 29:46.784
You've done this procedure
before, right?

29:46.786 --> 29:48.051
- Yes.
- Good.

29:48.053 --> 29:49.153
You ready?

29:49.155 --> 29:52.956
And 1, 2, 3.

29:52.958 --> 29:54.892
[ Groans loudly ]

29:54.894 --> 29:56.527
- What's the problem?
- I'm pulling, but nothing gives.

29:56.529 --> 29:57.461
I think the bone is stuck.

29:57.463 --> 29:59.129
I still don't feel a pulse.

29:59.131 --> 30:00.197
Okay, let me try.
Let me try.

30:00.199 --> 30:01.431
Go.

30:01.433 --> 30:03.267
[ Sophie groans ]

30:03.269 --> 30:05.269
Damn it. It's not reducing.
I don't know what's wrong.

30:05.271 --> 30:07.805
What's wrong is the bone must be
button-holed against a tendon,

30:07.807 --> 30:08.872
preventing it from moving.

30:08.874 --> 30:10.974
She needs ortho
and an O.R. now.

30:10.976 --> 30:12.543
It's not gonna happen.
Blood pressure's dropping.

30:12.545 --> 30:14.278
Okay,
we can use the c-scope

30:14.280 --> 30:16.280
to help visualize the problem
while we troubleshoot.

30:16.282 --> 30:18.048
That's ortho. Do we even have
one of those down here?

30:18.050 --> 30:20.150
Yeah. Dr. Taylor uses it
as a coat rack.

30:20.152 --> 30:21.451
I haven't used one of those
since med school.

30:21.453 --> 30:23.053
I can do it.

30:23.055 --> 30:24.421
I just finished
my ortho rotation.

30:24.423 --> 30:25.973
I assisted on dozens.

30:25.974 --> 30:27.524
Well, what are you waiting for?
Go get it!

30:27.526 --> 30:28.458
I keep paging him.
Nothing.

30:28.460 --> 30:30.994
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

30:30.996 --> 30:33.497
[ Cellphone beeps ]

30:33.499 --> 30:35.465
[ Ringing ]
Please pick up.

30:35.467 --> 30:36.500
[ Cellphone buzzing ]

30:36.502 --> 30:38.235
Leanne: Got it?
Neal: Got it.

30:38.237 --> 30:40.270
[ Sighs ] Neal.

30:40.272 --> 30:41.992
Pick up, pick up,
pick up, pick up, pick up.

30:46.045 --> 30:48.946
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]
[ Ringing ]

30:48.948 --> 30:52.015
Pick up, pick up, pick up.

30:52.017 --> 30:53.617
Did you page the chief?
Did you page maintenance?

30:53.619 --> 30:54.918
Maintenance is working on it.

30:54.920 --> 30:56.253
Sat is 60%.

30:56.255 --> 30:57.387
Okay.
I can't wait anymore.

30:57.389 --> 30:59.523
I have no choice.
I have to try.

30:59.525 --> 31:00.624
I thought you said
you couldn't do it.

31:00.626 --> 31:02.926
Yeah, well,
let's hope I was wrong.

31:02.928 --> 31:04.194
Okay.
See the meds I drew up?

31:04.196 --> 31:06.330
Slam each into her I.V. Now.

31:06.332 --> 31:08.365
Her larynx muscles
are too tense.

31:12.071 --> 31:14.071
[ Gasping ]

31:14.073 --> 31:16.240
Damn it.

31:16.242 --> 31:17.908
Ugh!

31:17.910 --> 31:19.343
Are you okay?
No.

31:19.345 --> 31:21.211
I'm not.
[ Sighs ]

31:21.213 --> 31:24.381
We need her head angled back
to do this.

31:24.383 --> 31:27.351
The straight tube
won't make a turn that easily.

31:27.353 --> 31:29.920
[ Sighs ]
Okay.

31:29.922 --> 31:32.089
Okay.

31:32.091 --> 31:34.091
[ Beeping continues ]

31:34.093 --> 31:37.194
Sat is 40%.
She is starting to Brady down.

31:37.196 --> 31:39.129
Get the crash cart ready.

31:46.272 --> 31:48.372
Okay.

31:49.241 --> 31:51.642
There!
I got it.

31:51.644 --> 31:53.343
Give me the bag.

31:53.345 --> 31:58.115
[ Panting ]

31:58.117 --> 31:59.683
[ Beeping slows ]

31:59.685 --> 32:02.252
Sats are rising.
Heart rate improving.

32:02.254 --> 32:04.688
[ Panting ]

32:08.527 --> 32:09.626
Malaya:
Shall I advance the image?

32:09.628 --> 32:10.694
Neal: Yep.

32:10.696 --> 32:12.162
[ Keyboard clacks ]

32:12.164 --> 32:13.997
Again.

32:13.999 --> 32:16.466
There.
See that fragment?

32:16.468 --> 32:18.101
It's laced itself onto a tendon

32:18.103 --> 32:19.503
like a button fits
into its hole.

32:19.505 --> 32:22.572
We just have to pull
exactly like this...

32:22.574 --> 32:24.641
And move the joint inferiorly...

32:24.643 --> 32:27.477
so that the fragment
moves superiorly.
Superiorly.

32:28.580 --> 32:30.280
[ Bone cracks ]

32:30.282 --> 32:32.349
We have blood flow back.

32:33.585 --> 32:37.087
Distal pulse is 2-plus.

32:37.089 --> 32:38.555
I'll get a splint.

32:38.557 --> 32:41.558
She still needs ortho,
possible vascular.

32:41.560 --> 32:43.226
Nice job.

32:45.631 --> 32:47.998
[ Object thuds ]

32:47.999 --> 32:50.366
Try not to paint yourself
into a corner like that again.

32:56.608 --> 32:59.009
What did you do?
What?

32:59.011 --> 33:01.445
Okay, look. I don't want to get
into your personal life.

33:01.447 --> 33:03.080
What are you talking about?
If you're sleeping with dudes
or whatever,

33:03.082 --> 33:04.247
hey, I don't care.
I didn't sleep around,
all right?

33:04.249 --> 33:05.482
Truvada?

33:05.484 --> 33:07.451
You called in a prescription
under my name?

33:07.453 --> 33:09.453
It's a drug
that gay guys take...

33:09.455 --> 33:11.855
You think I would have used your
number if I was hiding that?

33:13.993 --> 33:16.059
I got stuck
doing the labs on Ted.

33:16.061 --> 33:17.394
What?
Why didn't you tell me?

33:17.396 --> 33:19.563
I couldn't find you.
Well, send me a text.

33:19.565 --> 33:21.732
'Cause I just got a text from
the pharmacy saying that I...

33:21.734 --> 33:23.467
Why are you making such
a big deal about this, huh?

33:23.469 --> 33:25.068
Because I could really get
in trouble.

33:25.070 --> 33:26.203
Yeah, well, I could have
gotten HIV from this guy,

33:26.205 --> 33:27.721
so I think we're even.

33:27.722 --> 33:29.238
Okay, there's a less than 1%
chance of seroconversion.

33:29.241 --> 33:30.741
If you're on truvada,
it's even lower than that.

33:30.743 --> 33:33.043
So not in the mood
for a lecture.

33:33.045 --> 33:35.278
Okay, this is not a lecture!
See, this... this is talking.

33:35.280 --> 33:37.314
It's what friends do.
They talk.

33:37.316 --> 33:38.682
Do you even know
what it means to be a friend?

33:38.684 --> 33:41.318
I mean, seriously.
Have you ever had one before?

33:41.320 --> 33:43.687
Screw you.

33:43.689 --> 33:45.489
[ Door opens, closes ]

33:47.026 --> 33:49.192
Hey.

33:49.194 --> 33:51.361
She's gonna be all right.
Don't be scared.

33:51.363 --> 33:53.463
She's still
in the head mask, okay?

33:53.465 --> 33:56.133
He doesn't get scared.
Do you, kid?

34:01.106 --> 34:03.774
[ Respirator hissing ]

34:03.776 --> 34:06.443
[ Monitor beeping ]

34:06.445 --> 34:08.311
Neal: Hey.

34:11.183 --> 34:12.382
Just, uh, just checking in.

34:12.384 --> 34:13.650
I heard you had a tough one.

34:13.652 --> 34:15.786
Ever put a square peg
in a round hole?

34:15.788 --> 34:18.455
Yeah, it was like that.

34:18.457 --> 34:19.689
Look, I saw that you called.

34:19.691 --> 34:21.158
I was busy, but the truth is,

34:21.160 --> 34:23.126
I'm not supposed to pick up
the phone, anyway.

34:23.128 --> 34:25.395
If you weren't ready to deal
with the code bag on your own,

34:25.397 --> 34:26.329
you wouldn't be here.

34:26.331 --> 34:28.331
Thanks... I guess.

34:29.802 --> 34:31.234
We shouldn't have had
those drinks.

34:31.236 --> 34:34.704
Uh, it's made this whole thing
rather awkward.

34:34.706 --> 34:36.339
Not for me.

34:36.341 --> 34:37.808
Neal, we ran into each other
at breakfast

34:37.810 --> 34:39.843
and decided to have
a few bloody Marys.

34:39.845 --> 34:41.344
What is awkward about that?

34:41.346 --> 34:42.963
If you think
my mind is on anything

34:42.964 --> 34:44.581
other than being the best
possible doctor I can be,

34:44.583 --> 34:46.216
then you need to reconsider.

34:46.218 --> 34:47.551
Can I just say one thing?

34:47.553 --> 34:49.219
Mm-hmm.

34:51.123 --> 34:52.823
You're already a legend
downstairs.

34:52.825 --> 34:55.358
A medical journal called.

34:57.496 --> 34:59.162
Oh, you're full of it.

34:59.164 --> 35:00.197
Yeah, but I had you
for a second, didn't I?

35:00.199 --> 35:01.199
Ugh.

35:02.701 --> 35:04.634
Damn.

35:15.414 --> 35:17.681
I'm sorry to have bothered you.

35:17.683 --> 35:20.317
I was feeling a little nervous.

35:20.319 --> 35:22.853
Vitals seem okay.

35:22.855 --> 35:25.155
BP's a little low, but...

35:26.625 --> 35:27.657
Want to take a breath?

35:30.195 --> 35:34.531
I thought I came through that
transvenous thing just fine.

35:34.533 --> 35:37.801
You did.
Sounds okay.

35:39.438 --> 35:40.804
Tell me a story.

35:40.806 --> 35:42.606
What?

35:42.608 --> 35:43.707
A story.

35:43.709 --> 35:45.275
About you.

35:45.277 --> 35:46.743
Why me?

35:46.745 --> 35:48.745
I mean,
there's tons of doctors here.

35:48.747 --> 35:56.747
I see you, and I feel like
I'm looking at me at your age.

35:57.456 --> 36:01.525
It's the same bravado,
the steely eyes,

36:01.527 --> 36:05.462
the conquests,
the wall around the heart.

36:06.732 --> 36:08.298
You don't know a thing about me.

36:08.300 --> 36:09.900
Then tell me a story
about you.
No.

36:09.902 --> 36:12.569
I don't have any stories.
Start with
"I remember when"...

36:12.571 --> 36:15.672
No.
I remember when my father
bounced me on his knee.

36:15.674 --> 36:18.909
I remember when I fell in love
with my best friend.

36:18.911 --> 36:20.911
I remember my 17th birthday.

36:20.913 --> 36:22.746
I remember getting arrested.
Would you cut it out?

36:22.748 --> 36:25.682
I remember trying pot
for the first time.

36:25.684 --> 36:27.384
Coke.

36:27.386 --> 36:28.752
I remember the first time
I kissed someone.

36:28.754 --> 36:31.688
I remember that time
I saw "Titanic".

36:31.690 --> 36:33.223
Ah, you did, didn't you?

36:33.225 --> 36:34.658
I remember when they forgot me.

36:37.763 --> 36:39.896
It was on a Friday.
I was in third grade.

36:39.898 --> 36:42.232
They couldn't find my parents
for the whole weekend.

36:42.234 --> 36:43.934
I stayed with my teacher,
Mrs. Clarke.

36:43.936 --> 36:46.403
When they finally found
my mother,

36:46.405 --> 36:47.804
I didn't want to go back.

36:50.676 --> 36:52.309
Yeah, I wanted to stay
with Mrs. Clarke,

36:52.311 --> 36:57.747
with her clean sheets...
Full refrigerator.

36:59.585 --> 37:01.484
We're the same, kiddo.

37:02.821 --> 37:04.754
Exactly the same.

37:11.263 --> 37:12.496
You're right, by the way.

37:12.497 --> 37:13.730
That raft was big enough
for the both of them.

37:13.732 --> 37:15.832
[ Both chuckle ]

37:15.834 --> 37:17.300
Mm.

37:17.302 --> 37:21.905
Some advice from future you,
Dr. Savetti.

37:21.907 --> 37:23.540
¶¶

37:23.542 --> 37:27.310
You don't want to end up
like me...

37:27.312 --> 37:28.445
Alone.

37:28.447 --> 37:30.580
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

37:30.582 --> 37:32.716
[ Flatline ]

37:32.718 --> 37:34.985
Ted.

37:34.987 --> 37:36.553
Ted?

37:36.555 --> 37:38.255
Hey, no.
Don't do this.

37:39.324 --> 37:42.826
Epi... Bicarb...
Atropine.

37:42.828 --> 37:45.395
Come on, Ted.
Stay with me.

37:45.397 --> 37:47.664
Hold on, bud.
Hold on.

37:47.666 --> 37:49.599
Okay?
Come on!

37:49.601 --> 37:53.470
We got more stories, Ted.
We got more stories to tell.

37:53.472 --> 37:55.038
I need some help in here!

37:55.040 --> 37:59.342
Come on.
Come on.

38:01.313 --> 38:04.314
Come on, Ted.
We got more stories.

38:04.316 --> 38:05.482
Jesse:
I went over to phlebotomy.

38:05.484 --> 38:07.751
They're not taking
any more swabs.

38:07.753 --> 38:10.854
Carla shut it down.
She wants to save the baby.

38:10.856 --> 38:12.389
The problem with medicine is

38:12.391 --> 38:13.857
sometimes,
there's no good answer.

38:16.461 --> 38:18.695
It's amazing you two lasted
as long as you did.

38:18.697 --> 38:20.697
Who?
Carla and I?

38:20.699 --> 38:23.466
You're a thinker.
She's a feeler.

38:23.468 --> 38:24.768
You want her to listen

38:24.770 --> 38:27.437
to all the percentages,
the studies.

38:27.439 --> 38:28.905
Get her as many more years
as you can.

38:28.907 --> 38:30.373
What's wrong with that?

38:30.375 --> 38:32.542
She's feeling something
inside of her.

38:32.544 --> 38:34.077
That's what
she's listening to now.

38:34.079 --> 38:35.745
That's how
she's gonna make sense

38:35.747 --> 38:36.880
of what's left of her life.

38:36.882 --> 38:38.748
Try to understand that.

38:38.750 --> 38:40.383
I can't.

38:40.385 --> 38:42.385
She's given up already.

38:42.387 --> 38:45.088
I don't know how to do that.

38:47.926 --> 38:50.660
So I had a near-death
experience, huh?

38:50.662 --> 38:53.530
It wasn't near.
It was the real deal.

38:53.532 --> 38:56.466
I don't remember any of it,
though.

38:58.670 --> 39:00.770
Just know
that you were fearless.

39:00.772 --> 39:04.574
You did everything you could
to save her, and you did.

39:05.777 --> 39:09.045
¶¶

39:10.449 --> 39:11.748
Hi.

39:11.750 --> 39:13.750
Hi.

39:13.752 --> 39:15.485
You okay?

39:22.127 --> 39:25.095
I wanted to ask you something
on the boat,

39:25.097 --> 39:26.563
but I didn't get a chance.

39:30.902 --> 39:32.969
[ Gasps ]

39:37.776 --> 39:39.843
[ Laughs ]

39:40.979 --> 39:42.779
[ Sniffles ]

39:46.118 --> 39:48.151
Yes.
[ Sniffles ]

39:50.055 --> 39:52.155
How are they doing?

39:52.157 --> 39:55.592
They're alive.
They're in love.

39:55.594 --> 39:57.127
It's a pretty good combination.

39:57.129 --> 39:59.863
At least somebody's happy.

39:59.865 --> 40:01.030
Bad day?

40:01.032 --> 40:03.867
Ah, that kid
I was looking after...

40:03.869 --> 40:08.605
I let him watch center stage
from the observation deck.

40:08.607 --> 40:09.939
I, uh...

40:09.941 --> 40:11.775
I got to go to a hearing
on Friday.

40:11.777 --> 40:13.843
No good deed goes unpunished.

40:13.845 --> 40:15.745
Nope.

40:15.747 --> 40:17.747
I was thinking of spending
more time on my boat.

40:17.749 --> 40:18.882
You have a boat?

40:18.884 --> 40:21.151
Yeah.
The<i> wet dream.</i>

40:21.153 --> 40:22.986
Excuse me?

40:22.988 --> 40:24.087
The boat.
That's her name.

40:24.089 --> 40:27.891
Dr. Savetti,
this was nobody's fault.

40:27.893 --> 40:32.562
His heart just finally gave out.

40:33.965 --> 40:36.099
There was someone
he told us to call.

40:36.101 --> 40:39.769
Yeah.
His friend.

40:40.739 --> 40:42.672
I'll do it.

40:42.674 --> 40:44.507
You need to take care
of the body.

40:44.509 --> 40:45.642
Get him to the morgue.

40:47.512 --> 40:49.179
He shouldn't have died alone.

40:49.181 --> 40:52.916
He didn't.

40:52.918 --> 40:55.685
¶¶

40:55.687 --> 40:57.754
[ indistinct chatter ]

41:02.127 --> 41:04.928
Oh, leanne.
Good. You're still here.

41:04.930 --> 41:06.229
Headed home.
How about you?

41:06.231 --> 41:07.831
Soon.

41:07.833 --> 41:09.473
Would you like
to go out with me sometime?

41:14.606 --> 41:15.872
Excuse me?

41:15.874 --> 41:18.775
Lunch?

41:18.777 --> 41:20.944
Maybe a night before a day off.

41:20.946 --> 41:24.981
No.
I don't.

41:24.983 --> 41:27.550
Why?

41:27.552 --> 41:28.885
Is it because I'm black?

41:30.956 --> 41:32.755
Because I have a temper?

41:32.757 --> 41:34.090
You're Guthrie's son,
for starters.

41:34.092 --> 41:39.028
And... I don't go out.

41:39.030 --> 41:41.064
Ever.

41:43.568 --> 41:45.902
Look, I know about
what happened to you.

41:45.904 --> 41:47.971
The accident.

41:47.973 --> 41:50.707
I'm sorry.

41:50.709 --> 41:53.142
Look, when I was 15,
I found my mother

41:53.144 --> 41:56.179
lying on the bathroom floor
in a pool of blood

41:56.181 --> 41:57.514
with a gun in her hand.

41:58.984 --> 42:02.719
I mean, if you want to play
the grief Olympics,

42:02.721 --> 42:04.654
I'm a gold medalist.

42:04.656 --> 42:09.025
Uh...

42:09.027 --> 42:10.093
Good night, doctor.

42:13.198 --> 42:15.732
You know, it's okay.
You're just not ready yet.

42:15.734 --> 42:18.167
Have a good morning.

42:18.169 --> 42:19.769
It stopped raining,
uh, just so you know.
